## React Component Architecture

### File Structure
- Place components in `src/components/` directory
- Use PascalCase for component names: `UserCard.jsx`, `LoginForm.tsx`
- Separate container and presentational components appropriately
- Keep components small and focused (max 200 lines)

### TypeScript Usage
```typescript
// Interface definitions for props
interface UserCardProps {
  user: {
    id: number;
    name: string;
    email: string;
  };
  onClick?: () => void;
  loading?: boolean;
}

const UserCard: React.FC<UserCardProps> = ({ user, onClick, loading }) => {
  // Component implementation
};

export default UserCard;
```

## Code Quality Standards

### Hooks Usage
- Follow hook naming conventions: `useFetchData`, `useLocalStorage`
- Place hooks at the top of functional components
- Use custom hooks to encapsulate complex logic
- Avoid conditional hook calls

```typescript
// Good
const [data, setData] = useState(null);
const isLoading = useLoading();
const userData = useFetchUser(id);

// Avoid
if (condition) {
  const [data, setData] = useState(null);
}
```

### State Management
- Use React's built-in state for simple UI state
- Implement context for cross-component communication
- Use Redux Toolkit or Zustand for complex global state
- Memoize expensive calculations with `useMemo`
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders with `useCallback`

## Performance Optimization

### Component Rendering
- Use React.memo for pure components
- Implement virtualized lists for large datasets
- Lazy load components using React.lazy
- Optimize images and assets appropriately

### Data Fetching
```typescript
// Use useEffect with proper cleanup
useEffect(() => {
  const fetchData = async () => {
    try {
      const response = await api.fetchUsers();
      setUsers(response.data);
    } catch (error) {
      setError(error.message);
    }
  };

  fetchData();

  return () => {
    // Cleanup function
  };
}, []);
```

## Naming Conventions

### Variable and Function Names
- Use camelCase for variables: `currentUser`, `handleClick`
- Use PascalCase for components: `UserCard`, `LoginForm`
- Use UPPER_CASE for constants: `API_URL`, `MAX_RETRY_COUNT`

### File Names
- Use kebab-case for files: `user-card.jsx`, `login-form.tsx`
- Include file extension (.jsx, .tsx) for clarity

## Error Handling

### Component Error Boundaries
```typescript
class ErrorBoundary extends React.Component {
  constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = { hasError: false };
  }

  static getDerivedStateFromError(error) {
    return { hasError: true };
  }

  componentDidCatch(error, errorInfo) {
    console.error('Error caught by boundary:', error, errorInfo);
  }

  render() {
    if (this.state.hasError) {
      return <h1>Something went wrong.</h1>;
    }
    return this.props.children;
  }
}
```

## Accessibility Standards

### Semantic HTML
- Use appropriate HTML elements for content structure
- Apply ARIA attributes when needed
- Ensure keyboard navigation support
- Implement proper focus management

```typescript
// Example with accessibility in mind
<button 
  aria-label="Close modal"
  onClick={handleClose}
  type="button"
>
  ✕
</button>
```

## Testing Practices

### Component Testing
- Use React Testing Library (RTL) - the standard for 2026
- Test user interactions and DOM changes, not implementation details
- Mock external dependencies properly 
- Include edge case testing for props and state

```typescript
// Example test structure
describe('UserCard Component', () => {
  test('renders user information correctly', () => {
    const user = { name: 'John Doe', email: 'john@example.com' };
    render(<UserCard user={user} />);
    
    expect(screen.getByText('John Doe')).toBeInTheDocument();
    expect(screen.getByText('john@example.com')).toBeInTheDocument();
  });
});
```

